# Hardware Safety

This project drives real motors (Stewart steppers + ~144 module servos).

## Never do without explicit user approval

- `enable` / `pose` / `vel` / `jog` / `steps` on the Stewart board
- Servo `P` / calibrate / drive / demo that moves actuators
- Anything that energizes motors against mechanical limits

## Module servos — never leave energized

SG90 / PCA9685 module actuators **must not be left holding PWM**.
Stalled or loaded holds burn out servos.

Hard rules for agents and host tools:

- After every discrete `P` move: brief settle, then **`O` (channel) or `X` (all)**.
- Do not leave a channel energized across idle time, REPL prompts, or process exit.
- Active motion (jog pulse, sweep while running, demo jiggle) may energize
  only for the duration of that motion, then release immediately.
- `park` / pulse-and-limp is the correct pattern for “hold a pose” — friction,
  not continuous torque.
- On connect and on exit: release every channel (`X` or per-board `O` loops).
- Prefer `O` / `X` / `LX` over leaving PWM latched on the PCA9685.

Firmware backstop (`arduino/servo_calib`): each `P` auto-limps that channel
after **3s** (`HOLD`), independent of host heartbeats. Host silence still
triggers the **5s** `WATCHDOG`. Dynamic / timed tiles work by re-issuing `P`
before the hold window expires (or after limp — friction holds the pose).

## Always OK without asking

- Serial open + `help` / `status` / `?`
- LED-only commands (`L` / `LX` / `LN` / `LP`) when user asked for LED work
- Servo `X` / `O` / `LX` (release / all-off)
- Read-only probes (`lsusb`, port list, firmware identity)

## Camera notes

- MindVision HT-SUA134GM is **not** V4L2/`cv2.VideoCapture(0)`.
- Needs ARM64 MindVision `libMVSDK.so` — see `camera/README.md`.
- Kinect scripts are separate; do not assume Kinect is connected.

## When unsure

Default to **non-motion** smoke tests and ask before enabling drives.
